			<div class="article-correspondence layout-item fill-pattern-light">
		<div class="layout-item-intro">
			<h2>Correspondence</h2>
			<a class="xsmall link-alt" href="https://www.thesunmagazine.org/letter-to-the-editor">Write a Letter to the Editor&nbsp;&#9656;</a>
		</div>

		<div id="article-correspondences" class="correspondences correspondences-collapsed">
								<div class="block-correspondence" id="2658">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>Last week, I explained in depth to my boyfriend what I really wanted from our relationship and what I was willing to give. He hasn&rsquo;t called me since.</p>

<p>Last night, with swollen eyes and puffy face, I picked my son up from a birthday party and we drove home in silence. Waiting for me at home was the April issue of <strong>The Sun</strong>. Without bothering to clear the clutter off the kitchen table, I tipped my chair back, put my feet up, and read &ldquo;<a href="/article/1849">How I Lost My Mind, and Other Adventures</a>,&rdquo; by Poe Ballantine. Taking a silent cue from me, my son cleared a small space at the table and, with pens flying, drew a masterful <em>T. rex</em>, singing the entire time. It was a perfect moment.</p>

<p>When I read <strong>The Sun</strong>, I feel as though all the stupid things I do, all the pain I feel sometimes over trivial matters, all the not-knowing that lives within me next to the knowing is somehow OK. And as much of a junkie as I am for purpose and meaning, it is a relief to read plain honesty for honesty&rsquo;s sake. Thanks for saying it all so well.</p>

<p>Will you marry me?</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">Sue Jo Mitchell<br>Blue Hill, Maine</p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

								<div class="block-correspondence" id="2642">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>After reading &ldquo;<a href="/article/1849">How I Lost My Mind, and Other Adventures</a>&rdquo; and &ldquo;<a href="/article/1857">Man Standing under a Rocket Taking off for the Moon</a>&rdquo; [April 1997], we now know why Poe Ballantine is still in search of a publisher for his novel. He could use the services of an editor as well.</p>

<p>A quarter of the issue was devoted to the self-important drivel of this Jack Kerouac wannabe. Ballantine could learn a lesson from Dan Wakefield [&ldquo;<a href="/article/1859">The Clear Path to Creativity</a>,&rdquo; April 1997] on the value of clarity, true spiritual creativity, and discipline. As Wakefield said (quoting Murray Kempton), &ldquo;The devil never comes offering you something evil. The devil comes offering you a larger audience.&rdquo; May <strong>The Sun</strong> offer Ballantine less of an audience in the future.</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">Anne, Carla, Emily, Janet, and Laurie<br>Charlottesville, Virginia</p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

					</div>

				<div class="text-center">
			<button class="b b-1 xsmall js-b-readmore-correspondence" data-collapsible="#article-correspondences" data-label="Read More Letters">Read More Letters</button>
		</div>
			</div>
    
		<div class="article-correspondence-cta">
		<div class="cta cta-l1" data-url="https://www.thesunmagazine.org/letter-to-the-editor">
			<div class="cta-intro">
				<h5 class="cta-title alt-ff">Thinking about writing us a letter?</h5>
				<p class="cta-text">Give in to the temptation. We love getting mail. <br><span class="xsmall">(Of course, we reserve the right to edit.)</span></p>
			</div>
			<a href="https://www.thesunmagazine.org/letter-to-the-editor" class="cta-button b b-4 b-padding-tight small" data-label="Write Us A Letter!">Write Us A Letter!</a>
		</div>
	</div>
	

